      "grammarTip": "<p>Certain prepositions in German are always followed by the <strong>Akkusativ</strong> case. This means the noun and its article that follow the preposition must be in the accusative.</p><p>The most common accusative prepositions are often remembered with the acronym 'FUDGE-BO': <strong>für, um, durch, gegen, entlang - bis, ohne</strong>.</p><ul><li><strong>für:</strong> for (Das Geschenk ist <strong>für den</strong> Lehrer.)</li><li><strong>ohne:</strong> without (Ich gehe nie <strong>ohne meinen</strong> Schlüssel.)</li><li><strong>gegen:</strong> against / around (time) (Wir spielen <strong>gegen die</strong> Mannschaft.)</li><li><strong>um:</strong> around / at (time) (Wir treffen uns <strong>um 8</strong> Uhr.)</li><li><strong>durch:</strong> through (Ich gehe <strong>durch den</strong> Park.)</li><li><strong>bis:</strong> until / up to (Ich bleibe <strong>bis nächsten</strong> Montag.)</li><li><strong>entlang:</strong> along (Wir laufen <strong>den Fluss entlang</strong>. - Note: 'entlang' often comes after the noun.)</li></ul><h4>Article Changes in Akkusativ</h4><p>Remember, only the masculine article changes in the accusative case.</p><table class=\"grammar-table\"><thead><tr><th>Gender</th><th>Nominativ</th><th>Akkusativ</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Masculine (m)</td><td>der / ein</td><td><strong>den / einen</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Feminine (f)</td><td>die / eine</td><td>die / eine</td></tr><tr><td>Neuter (n)</td><td>das / ein</td><td>das / ein</td></tr><tr><td>Plural</td><td>die / keine</td><td>die / keine</td></tr></tbody></table>"
